{
  "doc_id": "27482",
  "text": "For CO2 absorption into aqueous MEA solutions, two reaction mechanisms, namely the zwitterion and the direct (termolecular) mechanisms, have been proposed. From the studies of Luo et al. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] and Aboudheir et al. [CITATION_3] , it was proposed that the direct (termolecular) reaction mechanism was able to represent the kinetic phenomena more precisely compared to the zwitterion mechanism. Putta et al. [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] developed both concentration based and activity based kinetic models by numerical solution of a discretized penetration theory based mass transfer model coupled with global optimization using a set of wetted wall mass transfer rate data for parameter fitting. The developed kinetic models were validated with data from three other independent experimental set-ups covering a wide range of conditions.",
